1. Definition and Typical Triggers
- RangeError is a built-in Error subtype in JavaScript used to indicate that a value is outside the set or range of allowed values for a function or operation.
- Common triggers: invalid array length (new Array(len) with illegal len), invalid numeric ranges passed to numeric methods (toExponential, toFixed, toPrecision), unrecognized normalization forms for String.prototype.normalize, or custom API parameter out-of-range conditions.

2. Constructor and Instance Properties
- Constructor: RangeError(message?: string)
- Instance property: name set to "RangeError", message string, stack available on Error.prototype.stack when supported by environment.
- RangeError inherits from Error; it is serializable and can be transferred across workers via structuredClone or postMessage.

3. When to throw RangeError in implementations
- Use RangeError when an argument value is numerically outside allowed bounds (e.g., index < 0 OR index >= length when a function requires an index in [0,length-1]).
- For invalid enumerated values where the argument is not one of expected strings, RangeError is acceptable (alternatively TypeError is sometimes used; prefer RangeError when the value is the wrong range/scale rather than wrong type).
- For API design: document which error type will be thrown for invalid inputs; prefer RangeError for numeric domain violations and size constraints.

Supplementary Details

Technical specifications and implementation details
- Throwing pattern: throw new RangeError('detailed message')
- Example validation flow: if (value < min || value > max) throw new RangeError(`value must be between ${min} and ${max}`)
- Serialization: RangeError objects are serializable via structuredClone in modern browsers and transferable between workers.

